# Self-verification rules (all projects)

- After implementing, verify it works before reporting success.
- Run the project's test command (npm test, pytest, go test, shellcheck) if one exists. Tests fail: fix and re-run. Never report "done" with known failures.
- Max 5 fix attempts before escalating.
- Reports show actual command output, not "all tests passed". Never "I believe this should work"; run the command.

## Commit style
- Conventional commits: feat(), fix(), docs(), refactor(), test(), chore(). One logical change per commit. Multi-file in one commit is fine; separate features get separate commits.

## Git branch naming

Format: `<type>/<short-slug>`. Type = `feat|fix|refactor|docs|test|chore|ingest`. Slug = 2-5 kebab-case words.

Rules:
- NO owner prefix on own repos (multi-contributor forks may use `<handle>/<type>/<slug>`).
- NO dates (exception: branches that ARE dated batches, e.g. `ingest/2026-04-22`).
- NO spec IDs, ticket numbers, phase markers (`SPEC-018`, `p1`, `phase-2`); put those in the PR body.
- Target 15-25 chars, hard cap 35. Kebab-case only.

Good: `feat/agent-skeleton`, `refactor/split-domain-folders`, `ingest/2026-04-22`, `docs/sa-rotation-sweep`.
Bad: `scaffold/spec-018-p1-agent-skeleton-2026-04-22` (date + spec ID + phase marker + vague type); `tieubao/feat/x` (owner prefix on own repo).

## When implementing from specs
- Read full spec first. Implement exactly what it says; no creative additions. Ambiguity: ask, don't guess. Run the spec's "Test" section verbatim after.

# macOS LaunchAgent / LaunchDaemon authoring (BTM-friendly)

Plists for launch agents/daemons must show in macOS BTM (System Settings → General → Login Items & Extensions) with the script's real name and exec icon. Two rules:

1. **`ProgramArguments[0]` is the absolute path to the script itself.** Not `/bin/sh`, not `/bin/bash`, not any interpreter wrapper. Script carries `#!/usr/bin/env bash` + `chmod +x`. Wrapping with `/bin/sh` collapses every script under one "sh" BTM row.
2. **The launcher script has NO `.sh` extension.** `.sh` files get the blank-page icon; bare names get the exec badge. Helper libraries `source`'d by the launcher keep `.sh`; only the top-level entry drops it.

Bad:
```xml
<key>ProgramArguments</key>
<array>
  <string>/bin/bash</string>
  <string>/path/to/mini.tide.sh</string>
</array>
```
BTM row: `bash` with exec icon. Useless.

Good:
```xml
<key>ProgramArguments</key>
<array>
  <string>/path/to/mini-tide</string>
</array>
```
BTM row: `mini-tide` with exec icon. Script has `#!/usr/bin/env bash` + `chmod +x`.

Verify post-deploy: `launchctl print system/<label> | grep -i program`, then visually confirm in BTM.

Third-party plists (Nix, OrbStack, etc.) exempt; we don't rewrite vendor-installed plists.
